title: Nuclear charge dispersion in the fission of 235U by protons of energy 20-85 MeV

x4freetext: Nuclear charge dispersion in the fission of 235U by
protons of energy 20-85 MeV

x4codes.shortRef: Jour: Canadian Journal of Chemistry, Vol.49, p.2205 (1971)

x4freetext: All irradiations were performed in
the internal circulating beam of the McGill proton
synchrocyclotron.
The targets were foils of 235U
having a superficial density of about 122 mg/cm2.
The target foil was sandwiched between two aluminum
foils 20 mu-m thick which served as guard foils for
fission products recoiling out of the target.
A 7.6 cm x 7.6 cm NaI(T1) crystal coupled to
a 400-channel pulse-height analyzer was used to
measure the y-radiations and K X-rays emitted by the
different nuclides.The annihilation radiation from the
decay by positron emission of 130Cs was measured by two
NaI(T1) crystals at 180 deg to each other coupled to a
gamma-gamma coincidence unit gated to receive the
511-keV photopeak.
An end-window gas-flow proportional counter
was used to measure the beta-radiation from 136Cs
Activation method with following
chemical separation of reaction products was used
Dissertation thesis at McGill University, Montreal
All irradiations were performed in the internal
circulating beam of the McGill proton
synchrocyclotron. Irradiations at beam current of
about 1 mu-A, were made at 10-MeV intervals in the
energy range 20-70 MeV, at 77 and 85 MeV.
